# Main Idea + Key Details

Research consistently shows:

# Reading Comprehension

is NOT:

```text id="m3r7qe"
remembering random facts
```

Strong readers learn to:

```text id="r8e2qe"
identify
important meaning
```

Students learn:

```text id="x4r9qe"
read text
→ identify topic
→ determine main idea
→ locate supporting details
→ explain meaning
```

This develops:

* comprehension
* summarizing
* attention to evidence
* critical thinking
* informational reading skills

This becomes:

# Meaning-Building Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p2r5qe"
every detail
=
main idea
```

or:

```text id="u9e1qe"
main idea
=
single favorite fact
```

Example:

students may read:

```text id="c6r3qe"
A passage about frogs
```

and choose:

```text id="k1e8qe"
frogs jump far
```

instead of:

```text id="n7r4qe"
frogs have features
that help them survive
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="t5e6qe"
important-idea reasoning
```

For Grade 3:

focus includes:

* topic
* main idea
* supporting details
* informational and narrative text

